<TEXT>Diagnosis:
-----------------
ulna fracture left after fall and collision while playing sports at 15-01-2016.

Medical history:
--------------------------
None

Technical examinations:
-----------------------
PREOPERATIVE
.............
RX lower arm left 25-01-2016
In comparison with earlier visit on 15/1/2016:
Checking of a comminuted fracture in the middle 1/3 part of the ulna diaphysis with conservative treatment:

- unchanged slightly shifted position of the distal segment to ulary with regard to the proximal
- no secundary shifting or angulation
- the fracture lines are still sharply visible: no increase in callus

POSTOPERATIVE
.............
RX lower arm left 28-01
- good alignment of fracture fragments, good reduction of fracture. Good position of the materials, no signs of loosening.

Current visit:
---------------
Your patient has received surgery on 28-01-2016. To stabilise the fracture, a plate and screw osteosynthesis was performed. Smooth procedure.

No complications postoperatively resulting in patient discharge from the hospital in good condition.

Further concerns:
--------------
- Mobilisation according to physiotherapy: stable
- Analgesia depending on need
Paracetemol 1g max 4x/day
If needed, Ibuprofen 600mg, max 3x/d and max 6 days, during meal.
If needed, Tramadol 50mg Co up to 4x1/d. Due to potential obstipation effect Movicol can be given, 1 sachet / day.
- Clexane 40mg SC injection 1/d up to 10 days postoperative.    
- The stitches were all intradermal with resobable wires. The tabs should be removed from 10 days post-operative, as soon as the wound allows.
- Furthermore dry and aseptic wound care.

We would like to see your patient for a check-up at the consultation of Prof. dr. NAME on 13-03-2016 at 3:45 PM. One hour before this appointment, the patient must report to the medical imaging department for a check-up radiography.

Yours sincerely
</TEXT>
